int-org-section.p:
In June 2018 the European Commission published proposals for the CAP in 2021-27. The proposals envisaged a CAP budget representing almost one-third of the total EU budget, to be split between direct support for farmers and market measures, and rural development; greater support per hectare would be provided for small and medium-sized farms, and member states would have increased flexibility to transfer a percentage of their CAP allocations between direct payments and rural development, and to environmental and climate measures. In December 2020 a CAP budget (in current prices) of some €386,600m. for 2021-27 was approved. The implementation of the proposed reforms, including efforts to improve environmental, economic and social sustainability as part of the EU’s new environmental strategy, the European Green Deal (see 

                    Energy, Environment and Climate

), were postponed until 1 January 2023, owing to ongoing negotiations between the European Parliament and the Council. In the mean time, existing CAP measures remained in place. In June 2021 the two institutions concluded a provisional political agreement on the new CAP, which was formally adopted in December. During 2023-27 the CAP was to focus on 10 principal objectives: ensuring a fair income for agricultural workers; competitiveness; improving the position of farmers in relation to the food value chain; action to combat climate change; care of the environment; preservation of landscapes; generational renewal; protecting rural areas; protecting both food quality and health; and fostering knowledge and innovation. Twenty-eight CAP strategic plans were designed and approved (one for each member state, with two for Belgium) in the context of these objectives and the new CAP began on 1 January 2023. Green Deal targets for 2030 were included in the so-called Farm to Fork Strategy, announced by the Commission in May 2020, focusing on sustainability in food production, distribution and consumption, as well as on reducing food waste, and on the EU’s Biodiversity Strategy for 2030. The new CAP provided for a more equitable division of CAP income support, with member states expected to allocate 10% of their direct payments to a redistributive income support tool, to allow for higher payments for smaller-scale farmers.

In December 2006 the Council adopted a decision establishing the Seventh Framework Programme for research and technological development (FP7, which was implemented during 2007-13), and also established the Seventh Framework Programme of Euratom, for nuclear research and training activities in 2007-11. In October 2010 the Commission adopted a communication on the Innovation Union, designed to help the EU economy to recover from economic crisis, by encouraging global competitiveness and innovation. FP7 was superseded by the EU Framework Programme for Research and Innovation, `Horizon 2020’, covering 2014-20, with a budget of some €80,000m. In 2015, under Horizon 2020, the three policy objectives of open innovation, open science, and open to the world were established. Horizon 2020 was superseded by Horizon Europe for 2021-27, with a budget of €76,400m. (in 2018 prices), plus additional funding of some €8,000m. Horizon Europe introduced a new European Innovation Council (EIC), intended to complement the work of the EIT. The EIC, which became operational in 2018-20 during a pilot phase, supports innovation by means of two funding instruments: the EIC Pathfinder supports researchers investigating `high risk, high gain’ new technologies, while the EIC Accelerator supports innovative projects being developed by small and medium-sized Enterprises (SMEs). The EIC became fully operational in March 2021, and a new European Innovation Council and SMEs Executive Agency was established in Brussels. The EU’s research and innovation budget for 2021-27 (in 2018 prices) also allocated €1,757m. to the Euratom Research and Training Programme and €5,000m. to the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER—see 
Energy, Environment and Climate
).

The treaty establishing the European Atomic Energy Community (Euratom) came into force on 1 January 1958. This was designed to encourage the growth of the nuclear energy industry in the Community by conducting research, providing access to information, supplying nuclear fuels, building reactors and establishing common laws and procedures. A common market for nuclear materials was introduced in 1959 and there is a common insurance scheme against nuclear risks. In 1977 the Commission began granting loans on behalf of Euratom to finance investment in nuclear power stations and the enrichment of fissile materials. An agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) entered into force in the same year, to facilitate co-operation in research on nuclear safeguards and controls. The EU’s Joint Research Centre (JRC, see 

                    Research and Innovation

) conducts research on nuclear safety and the management of radioactive waste.

The EU promoted trans-European networks (TENs, see also 

                    Transport

), with the aim of developing European energy, telecommunications and transport through the interconnection and opening up of national networks. Revised guidelines for the TEN-Energy (TEN-E) programme were adopted by the Council in July 2006, and a revised TEN-E regulation entered into force in June 2022, which established new rules on cross-border energy infrastructure; aimed to further develop the EU offshore strategy and encourage co-operation between member states in the generation of offshore renewable energy; and supported hydrogen transport networks. In November 2013 the European Parliament (EP) approved the EU’s new infrastructure policy, with the introduction of the new Connecting Europe Facility (CEF) for the fields of transport, energy and telecommunications. The CEF was allocated funds for energy of €5,180m. for 2021-27 (in 2018 prices).

In July 2020 the Commission adopted new strategies for the integration of energy systems and for investment in the use of clean hydrogen technologies to help to achieve its objectives. It was envisaged that the contribution of renewable hydrogen to EU energy production would increase from less than 2% in 2018 to 13%-14% by 2050. In July 2021 the Commission adopted proposals on `Delivering the European Green Deal’, confirming a Europe 2030 emissions reduction target of at least 55% by 2030 (`Fit for 55’), in comparison with 1990 levels, and the intention for the EU to be `carbon neutral’ by 2050. Five pieces of `Fit for 55’ legislation were adopted by the Council in April 2023, revising the EU ETS (see above). In its programme for 2023, the Commission stated that it aimed to establish a `hydrogen bank’ that would assist in the scaling up of the EU green hydrogen economy and invest in developing a hydrogen market; a first pilot auction for €800m. in subsidies payable to producers of renewable hydrogen was launched in November. In February 2023 the Commission put forward the Green Deal Industrial Plan, which would aim to increase the production capacity of key green technologies in the EU (see 

                    Internal Market, Industry, Entrepreneurship and Small and Medium-sized Enterprises

).

In addition to the Enterprise Europe Network, the EU’s other information services for business include the Community Research and Development Information Service (CORDIS, see 

                    Research and Innovation

) and the Your Europe portal (europa.eu/youreurope/business/index_en.htm), which provides practical information on doing business in Europe. In addition, more than 106 certified and 43 associate Business and Innovation Centres operate in the EU countries and outside the EU, with a mission to promote entrepreneurship and the creation of innovative businesses, and to assist existing companies to enhance their prospects through innovation.

In 2021-27 the EU’s new Single Market Programme (see 
Internal Market, Industry, Entrepreneurship and Small and Medium-sized Enterprises
) was to finance activities relating to consumer protection and to the protection and sustainability of the food supply chain, required in order to ensure the efficient operation of the Single Market. In December 2020 the Commission proposed a new Digital Services Act and a Digital Markets Act, which aimed to protect consumers, and their rights, online (see 
Communications, Content, Technology and the Digital Single Market
).

In September 2009 the Commission adopted proposals for the creation of a European Systemic Risk Board (ESRB), which was to monitor and assess risks to the stability of the financial system as a whole; and a European System of Financial Supervisors (ESFS), with the capacity to address recommendations and warnings issued to member states and to the European supervisory authorities. The ESFS comprised three European Supervisory Authorities (ESAs): a Euro­pean Banking Authority; a European Securities and Markets Authority; and a European Insurance and Occupational Pensions Authority, to help rebuild confidence, unify financial rules, resolve problems involving cross-border firms, and prevent the accumulation of risks that could undermine the stability of the financial system. In September 2010 the EP endorsed the new supervisory framework, which was confirmed by ministers responsible for the economy and for finance (the ECOFIN Council) in November. The three ESAs and the ESRB were established in January 2011 to replace the supervisory committees hitherto in place. In December 2012 EU ministers responsible for finance approved plans to deepen and safeguard economic stability through the creation of a banking union (see 
Economic Co-operation
). A Bank Resolution and Recovery Directive (BRRD) was adopted, introducing harmonized procedures for the management of insolvent financial institutions. Member states were required to implement the Directive by the end of 2014 (however, 11 states failed to do so).

In May 2014 the European Commission published an initial comprehensive review of its financial regulation framework, following the proposal of more than 40 reform measures in the wake of the economic and financial crisis in the eurozone. In November 2016 the Commission proposed a number of amendments to the CRD, as part of a package of legislative measures that also sought to amend the Capital Requirements Regulation, the BRRD and the Single Resolution Mechanism Regulation (see 
Economic Co-operation
), in order to address structural weaknesses and further bolster the European economy.
